te responses to identity claims worldwide. Their case studies focus on key issues where identity is central to public policy – such as the construction of census categories, interpretation of antidiscrimination norms, and assessment of indigenous rights. By illuminating both the risks and opportunities of institutional responses to diversity, this volume shows that public institutions can either enhance or distort the benefits of identity politics. Much depends on the agency of citizens and the ability of institutions to adapt to success and failure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnicity -- Political aspects. 0aIdentification (Religion) -- Political aspects. 0aMulticulturalism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Cultural Policy.2bisacsh1 aArmony, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaman, Lori G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerman, Bruce J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisenberg, Avigail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisenberg, Avigail, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHooker, Juliet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJefremovas, Villia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKymlicka, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKymlicka, Will, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLaliberté, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLépinard, Eléonore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaclure, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNobles, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary